      "evidence": [
        "frontend/src/features/trading/EventTradePanel.tsx:6-29 (TradeReceipt definition with impactScore thresholds)",
        "frontend/src/features/trading/EventTradePanel.tsx:7-8 (impactColor conditional: >0.5 danger, >0.2 warning, else muted)",
        "frontend/src/features/trading/EventTradePanel.tsx:106-109 (TradeReceipt rendered on mutation.isSuccess)"
      ],
      "uncertainty": "Testing inline CSS variables (var(--color-danger)) in jsdom may require checking the raw style string rather than computed color values, since jsdom doesn't resolve CSS variables. May need to assert on the style.color property directly."
    },
    {
      "question_id": "q4",
      "answer": "Both early-return-null conditions should be tested. EventTradePanel returns null for (1) market.status !== 'active' (line 38) and (2) !isConfigured (line 39). Unlike TradingPanel which shows 'Set your Account ID' for unconfigured sessions, EventTradePanel renders nothing in both cases. Tests should use container.firstChild or queryByText to verify nothing is rendered. Testing both guard clauses is lightweight (2 small tests) and ensures both protective conditions work. The 'session integration' aspect of the task maps to testing the unconfigured session guard.",
      "confidence": 0.95,
      "evidence": [
        "frontend/src/features/trading/EventTradePanel.tsx:38 (if market.status !== 'active' return null)",
        "frontend/src/features/trading/EventTradePanel.tsx:39 (if !isConfigured return null)",
        "frontend/src/__tests__/TradingPanel.test.tsx:104-110 (TradingPanel shows 'Set your Account ID' for unconfigured)"
      ],
      "uncertainty": "None — the component code is clear about both conditions."
    },
    {
      "question_id": "q5",
      "answer": "The test should assert the exact formula structure. The formula is the core semantic payload of event trading — it encodes what is being traded. The structure is: formula: [[{ variableId: market.id, outcomeId: selectedOutcome, negated: false }]]. Since this is a nested array of objects with specific field names, asserting the exact structure catches construction bugs (wrong nesting, missing fields, wrong boolean). The TradingPanel test asserts exact payload structure (target.kind, target.outcomeId, target.probability), so asserting formula structure follows the same convention. Use toEqual for deep matching on the formula array.",
      "confidence": 0.9,
      "evidence": [
        "frontend/src/features/trading/EventTradePanel.tsx:48-56 (mutation.mutate payload with formula structure)",
        "frontend/src/__tests__/TradingPanel.test.tsx:156-164 (TradingPanel test asserts exact payload fields)",
        "frontend/src/lib/api/types.ts:324-329 (EventTradePayload type with formula: Array<Array<{...}>>)"
      ],
      "uncertainty": "The formula structure is currently simple (single conjunction with one literal). If it becomes more complex in the future, exact assertions would be more brittle — but for now it's the right choice."
    }
  ],
  "assumption_checks": [
    {
      "assumption_id": "a1",
      "verdict": "CORRECT",
      "confidence": 0.95,
      "impact": "The test file should follow the exact same pattern: mock useSession at module level, mock useEventTrade (instead of useProbabilityEdit), use vi.mocked, create defaultMutationState helper, use renderWithProviders from ./helpers. The only difference is mocking useEventTrade instead of useProbabilityEdit."
    },
    {
      "assumption_id": "a2",
      "verdict": "CORRECT",
      "confidence": 0.95,
      "impact": "The Market type is the same for both components. The mockMarket fixture from TradingPanel.test.tsx includes all fields EventTradePanel uses: id, status, outcomes, marginals. It can be reused as-is. EventTradePanel also uses market.id as variableId in the formula, which maps to market.id (not market.variableId)."
    },
    {
      "assumption_id": "a3",
      "verdict": "CORRECT",
      "confidence": 0.95,
      "impact": "Confirmed by reading the component. EventTradePanel has no slider input. The 'probability input' refers to the outcome selector dropdown which displays marginal probabilities in each option label and shows a Price label when an outcome is selected."
    },
    {
      "assumption_id": "a4",
      "verdict": "CORRECT",
      "confidence": 0.95,
      "impact": "Confirmed by existing test patterns. TradingPanel.test.tsx and ConditionalEditor.test.tsx both use crypto.randomUUID() without mocking, and assert idempotencyKey with toBeDefined(). No polyfill or mock needed."
    },
    {
      "assumption_id": "a5",
      "verdict": "CORRECT",
      "confidence": 0.9,
      "impact": "The test scope is appropriate. Recommended test cases: (1) null render for inactive market, (2) null render for unconfigured session, (3) rendering form elements (Quick Trade heading, side toggle, outcome selector, trade button), (4) buy/sell toggle interaction, (5) outcome selection with price display, (6) trade submission with correct payload including exact formula structure, (7) pending state (Submitting text, disabled button), (8) success with TradeReceipt showing orderId and asset delta values, (9) error display. Optionally add 2-3 TradeReceipt color threshold tests for impactScore variations."
    }
  ],
  "spawn_children": false,
  "children": []
}

